{"title_page": "John Safran", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian filmmaker and radio personality}}\n{{distinguish|text=the American author [[Jonathan Safran Foer]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   =\n| name               =  John Safran\n| honorific_suffix   =\n| image              =  John Safran.jpg\n| image_size         =\n| alt                =\n| caption            = Safran at the 2009 [[Melbourne International Film Festival]]\n| birth_name = John Michael Safran\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1972|08|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]]\n| residence          =\n| nationality        = Australian\n| other_names        = Yehoshua Safran<br />{{small|({{lang-he|\u05d9\u05b0\u05d4\u05d5\u05b9\u05e9\u05bb\u05c1\u05e2\u05b7 \u05e1\u05e4\u05e8\u05df}})}}\n| citizenship        =\n| education          =\n| occupation         = [[Documentarian]]<br />[[Journalist]]<br />[[Radio personality|Radio presenter]]<br />[[Author]]\n| years_active       = 1997 - present\n| known_for          = ''[[John Safran's Music Jamboree]]''<br /> ''[[John Safran vs God]]''<br /> ''[[Race Around the World]]''<br /> [[Sunday Night Safran]]\n| notable_works      = ''[[Murder in Mississippi (book)|Murder in Mississippi]]''\n| style              =\n| home_town          =\n| spouse             =  <!-- Use article title or common name -->\n| partner            =  <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| children           =\n| parents            = \n| mother             = Gitl Obronzka\n| father             = Alex Safran\n| relatives          = Margaret (sister)\n| family             =\n| callsign           =\n| awards             =\n| website            = {{URL|http://www.johnsafran.com}}\n| signature          =\n| signature_size     =\n| signature_alt      =\n| footnotes          =\n}}\n\n'''John Michael Safran''' ({{Hebrew name 1 | \u05d9\u05b0\u05d4\u05d5\u05b9\u05e9\u05bb\u05c1\u05e2\u05b7 \u05e1\u05e4\u05e8\u05df | Yehoshua Safran}}; born 13 August 1972)<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Pat Mesiti, John Watson and Deborah Landis|episode-link= |url=https://soundcloud.com/triplejsundaynightsafran/pat-mesiti-john-watson-and|access-date= |series=Sunday Night Safran |series-link= |first= |last= |network=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|station=Triple J |date= 14 May 2016|season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> is an Australian radio personality, satirist, documentary maker and author, known for combining humour with religious, political and ethnic issues. First gaining fame appearing in ''[[Race Around the World]]'' in 1997, Safran went on to produce a series of documentaries, television shows and host radio programs.\n\nSafran is known for his television stunts, which include placing a fatwa on Australian television host [[Rove McManus]], sneaking nine young men into an exclusive [[Melbourne]] [[nightclub]] by disguising them as members of American [[nu metal]] band [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]], running through [[Jerusalem]] wearing nothing but the beanie and scarf of [[St Kilda Football Club]], driving a remote controlled seagull with a cigarette onto the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]], and his confrontation with tabloid current affairs host [[Ray Martin (television presenter)|Ray Martin]].\n\nCurrently, he works as a journalist and released a book, ''[[Depends What You Mean By Extremist]]'', in May 2017.<ref name=\"depends\">{{cite web|url=https://penguin.com.au/books/depends-what-you-mean-by-extremist-9781926428772|title=Depends What You Mean by Extremist: Going Rogue with Australian Deplorables |publisher=Penguin Books Australia}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSafran was born in [[Melbourne]] to Jewish parents.<ref name=\"abc.net.au\">{{Cite episode |title=John Safran |episode-link= |url=http://www.abc.net.au/gnt/history/Transcripts/s1217450.htm|access-date= |series=George Negus Tonight |series-link= |first=George |last=Negus |network=Australian Broadcasting Commission |station= |date=11 October 2004 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> His maternal grandparents were [[History of the Jews in Poland|Polish Jewish]] [[Bundism|Bundists]].<ref name=\"abc.net.au1\">{{Cite episode |title=John Safran |episode-link= |url=http://www.abc.net.au/sundayprofile/stories/s1383760.htm |access-date= |series=Sunday Profile |series-link= |first=Monica |last=Attard |network=Australian Broadcasting Commission |station= |date=5 June  2005 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> Safran's mother, Gitl, was born in [[Uzbekistan]] as they were fleeing their home country for Australia.<ref name=\"smh.com.au1\">{{cite news |last=Doreian |first=Robyn |date=29 September 2013 |title=What I know about women |url=http://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/what-i-know-about-women-20130924-2ubvz.html |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |location=Sydney, New South Wales, Australia |access-date= }}</ref> She died in 2003.<ref name=\"smh.com.au\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/what-i-know-about-women-20130924-2ubvz.html|title=What I know about women|work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> His paternal ancestors were [[History of the Jews in Germany|German Jews]] and left shortly before the rise of [[Nazi Germany]].<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Katrina Lucas, Guy Rundle and Alex Safran|episode-link= |url=http://mpegmedia.abc.net.au/triplej/safran/safran_2014_12_07.mp3 |access-date= |series=Sunday Night Safran |series-link= |first= |last= |network=Australian Broadcasting Commission |station=Triple J |date=7 December 2014 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> He has one older sister, Margaret.\n\nHe grew up in [[Balwyn North]] and attended North Balwyn Primary School, [[Balwyn High School]] and [[Yeshivah College, Australia|Yeshivah College]] from Year 8 onwards.<ref name=\"abc.net.au1\"/><ref name=\"smh.com.au\"/> He describes himself at Yeshivah, an all-boys Orthodox Jewish school, as being \"the least religious kid in the most religious school in Australia\".<ref name=\"abc.net.au\"/> His best friends at Yeshivah were George Weinberg, Jeremy Weinstein, Raph Brous and Saskia Greta Sansom.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Nick Cater, Andreas Dalsgaard and Charles Virtue |episode-link= |url=https://soundcloud.com/triplejsundaynightsafran/nick-cater-andreas-dalsgaard |access-date= |series=Sunday Night Safran |series-link= |first= |last= |network=Australian Broadcasting Commission |station=Triple J |date=9 June 2013 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes=74:50 |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref>\n\nAfter school he studied journalism at [[RMIT University]]. He eventually dropped out without completing his degree and began work in advertising for [[Clemenger Harvie]]. During this time he also worked as a copywriter for [[Mazda]], [[Village Roadshow]] and [[Sea World (Australia)|Sea World]], where he wrote the company's jingle.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Dr Clare Wright, David Wilcock, Anupam Sharma, Sharon Johal and Jason Callope |episode-link= |url=https://soundcloud.com/triplejsundaynightsafran/dr-clare-wright-david-wilcock |access-date= |series=Sunday Night Safran |series-link= |first= |last= |network=Australian Broadcasting Commission |station=Triple J |date=10 June 2010 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Motchkin building.jpg|thumb|Yeshivah College, Melbourne]]\nDuring his final year in high school, Safran formed the hip-hop group [[Raspberry Cordial]] with his friend Chris Lumsden. They played to some success, receiving high rotation airplay on the city's community radio, playing many gigs in Melbourne and coming second in the [[RMIT University|RMIT]] [[Battle of the Bands]] competition. Their debut album was ''Melbourne Tram'', of which Safran apparently has hundreds of unsold cassettes in his bedroom to this day.\n\nAfter winning a government youth music initiative, they followed up with ''Taste Test'', of which 500 copies were pressed. Of those only 93 sold, so the remaining 407 had to be crushed. He said that the world just \"wasn't ready for white rappers then\" and Raspberry Cordial \"broke down the wall that [[Eminem]]'s been able to walk through.\"<ref name=\"abc.net.au2\">{{Cite episode |title=John Safran |episode-link= |url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/enoughrope/transcripts/s892185.htm |access-date= |series=Enough Rope |series-link= |first=Andrew |last=Denton |network=Australian Broadcasting Commission |station= |date=30 June 2003 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref>\n\n==''Race Around the World''==\n{{Main article|Race Around the World}}\nSafran's first experience of national fame came via ''Race Around the World'', a television competition for young [[Television documentary|documentarians]] run by the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]. In his audition tape, Safran was required to submit ten seconds of black, but instead he submitted ten seconds of [[Black Sabbath]].<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Scarlet de Mason, Adam Shand and Varcha Sidwell |episode-link= |url=https://soundcloud.com/triplejsundaynightsafran/pagan-scarlet-de-mason |access-date= |series=Sunday Night Safran |series-link= |first= |last= |network=Australian Broadcasting Commission |station=Triple J |date=22 January 2012 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref>\n\nSafran started the race off timid and tame, being locked inside an [[Osaka Municipal Subway|Osaka subway station]] in his first entry. However, he quickly broke what he called the \"fear barrier\" to film his now famous segments. He ran [[streaking]] naked through the streets of [[Jerusalem]] wearing only the scarf and beanie of his favourite football club, [[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]] to prove that God is Jewish (St Kilda's only Grand Final win fell on the same day as [[Yom Kippur]]).<ref name=\"abc.net.au2\"/> He was baptised and placed a [[Haitian Vodou|Voodoo]] curse on his ex-girlfriend in the [[Ivory Coast]].<ref name=\"abc.net.au2\"/> He snuck into [[Disneyland]] via a work area and attached information plaques he made about founder [[Walt Disney]] to a display (highlighting little known Disney \"facts\" such as Walt Disney's alleged early support for [[Adolf Hitler]]) and got a Catholic priest to review [[death metal]] music.\n\nSafran's segments scored well with both the judges and the public audience, Safran topped the viewer poll. He was, however, disqualified for a segment taped in a [[confessional]] booth (the program forbade [[hidden camera]] footage), the disqualification of the segment and subsequent loss of points meant that he finished last in the first season of ''Race Around the World''.\n\n==After the race (1997-2002)==\nAfter this brush with fame the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] commissioned two 30-minute TV pilots from Safran.\n\nOne pilot called ''John Safran: Media Tycoon'' focused on the media industry, airing in 1998. It became famous for a segment, involving then host of tabloid current affairs TV show ''[[A Current Affair (Australian TV series)|A Current Affair]]'', where Safran harassed him in the style characteristic of ''A Current Affair'' by sorting through his bin, which was later satirised by comedian [[Shaun Micallef]]. [[Ray Martin (television presenter)|Ray Martin]]  had set-up members of the Paxton family. Safran and one of the victims, Shane Paxton, turned up to [[Ray Martin (television presenter)|Ray Martin]]'s home. Martin and his wife Dianne physically threatened Safran.<ref name=\"abc.net.au2\"/> Martin's wife ripped apart Safran's Papier M\u00e2ch\u00e9 hat and Ray grabbed Safran by the collar, prompting Shane Paxton to intervene. Martin was in contact with the ABC and specifically warned Safran in the segment that he's spoken to Roger Grant the then Head of Corporate Affairs at the ABC.<ref name=\"tvtonight.com.au\">{{cite magazine |last=Knox |first=David |date=26 April 2014 |title=John Safran still a sore point for Ray Martin |url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2014/04/john-safran-still-a-sore-point-for-ray-martin.html |magazine=TV Tonight |location=Australia|publisher= |access-date= }}</ref> Martin's connection with this executive at the ABC is suspected to be a reason the series never made it to air. The Ray Martin segment was later played on ''[[Media Watch (TV program)|Media Watch]]'', ''John Safran: The Lost Pilot'' and on YouTube.<ref name=\"tvtonight.com.au\"/> In 2014, Martin still appeared bitter about the incident, calling Safran a \"serial pest\".<ref name=\"tvtonight.com.au\"/>\n\nThe second pilot was titled ''John Safran: Master Chef''. This pilot focused on the food industry. Notably it featured a cooking segment where Safran prepared a beef dish. The twist comes when he arrives in an abattoir and shows detailed footage of cows being slaughtered to complete the dish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.craigmelville.com/safranabc/files/page25-1067-pop.html|title=Discontinued -- Prosite|author=Behance|publisher=|access-date=18 March 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080330002352/http://www.craigmelville.com/safranabc/files/page25-1067-pop.html|archive-date=30 March 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> Though all unsuccessful, the pilots became hits via the Internet among university students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fuck-the-skull-of-jesus.mit.edu/safran.html|title=John Safran TV Pilots|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041023085204/http://fuck-the-skull-of-jesus.mit.edu/safran.html|archivedate=23 October 2004|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Safran also recorded a parody of [[Baz Luhrmann]]'s song \"[[Everybody's Free (To Wear Sunscreen)]]\" entitled \"Not the Sunscreen Song\" which includes lines such as \"Never live in [[Adelaide]], it's a hole\" and \"Remember, you can't get pregnant the first time you have sex\". It peaked at No. 20 in 1998 and was nominated for an [[ARIA Music Awards|ARIA]]. In [[Triple M]]'s ''2005 Greatest Songs Ever Written and Performed Since the Beginning of Time'' poll, \"Not the Sunscreen Song\" came in at #706 \u2013 one spot above \"[[Superstition (song)|Superstition]]\" by [[Stevie Wonder]].<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nHZWrET2CUA|title=YouTube|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nSafran also presented segments for the [[Seven Network]]'s now defunct ''[[Late Report]]'', some were also screened in the United Kingdom with [[Channel 4]]'s ''[[Disinformation (TV series)|Disinformation]]'' program. Safran attained police attention for a stunt to try and coerce [[cricket]]er [[Shane Warne]] into breaking a \"no smoking\" clause in an advertising contract with a nicotine gum manufacturer. Safran drove a remote controlled seagull with a cigarette onto the MCG pitch during a match. He was arrested for \"[[pitch invasion]]\", but the charges were dropped.<ref name=\"abc.net.au2\"/>\n\n==Documentaries==\n===''Music Jamboree''===\n{{Main article|John Safran's Music Jamboree}}\nIn 2002, Safran launched his documentary series ''John Safran's Music Jamboree''. On one occasion Safran and his crew stormed the courtyard of his former school and amid shocked religious students and teachers, he and his crew began to dance to the song \"[[Footloose (song)|Footloose]]\". He was also able to gain entry into an exclusive Melbourne night club by dressing up nine men as the band [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Moskovitch |first=Greg |date=11 November 2014 |title=John Safran's 11 Greatest Music Moments |url=http://www.tonedeaf.com.au/425149/john-safrans-top-11-music-moments.htm |newspaper=Tone Deaf |location=Australia |access-date= }}</ref> Screened on [[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]] on Saturday nights, it opened Safran's work to youth 12 to 20 years old, who had not seen the original ''Race Around the World'' material. The show impressed the [[Australian Film Institute]] so much that it won an [[Australian Film Institute Awards|AFI award]] in 2003 for \"Best Comedy Series\" [https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/afi-award-winners-list-20031122-gdhu0y.html]\n\n===''John Safran vs God''===\n{{Main article|John Safran vs God}}\nIn August 2004 he debuted his new show ''John Safran vs God'', also on the SBS television network. The first seven episodes were typical Safran informative satire. The series' finale featured Safran being [[exorcism|exorcised]] of demons which had supposedly [[Demonic possession|possessed]] him during his dabblings with world religions. The exorcism was performed by well-known Christian fundamentalist [[Bob Larson]]. It has been claimed that Safran's behaviour during the exorcism was faked.{{Citation needed|date=April 2016}}  Safran has neither confirmed nor denied faking his behaviour, but in an interview with an Australian radio personality, Safran did say that he \"felt something was going on\", and that \"there was something about the expression on my face\". In an interview on [[Andrew Denton]]'s ''[[Enough Rope]]'' program, he claimed that he had no memory of the events during the exorcism, and stated that the footage shown on the show was merely the most interesting from hours of footage. ''John Safran vs God'' won a 2005 [[Australian Film Institute Awards|AFI Award]] for \"Best Comedy Series\".[https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/afi-award-winners-20051127-gdmixp.html]\n\nBefore the exorcism, Safran went to [[Mozambique]] to have a curse, previously placed on the [[Australia national association football team|Australian national football team]] by a now-deceased witch doctor, lifted. He and former Australian football team captain [[Johnny Warren]] were covered in chicken's blood in the process. Subsequently, on 16 November 2005, [[Football World Cup 2006 - Oceania-South America Qualification Playoff|Australia qualified]] for the [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] for the first time since 1974.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sygall |first=David |date=20 November 2005 |title=Socceroos owe it all to one man - and it isn't Hiddink |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/football/socceroos-owe-it-all-to-one-man--and-it-isnt-hiddink/2005/11/19/1132017026017.html|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald |location=Sydeny, New South Wales, Australia |access-date= }}</ref>\n\n===''Speaking in Tongues''===\n{{Main article|Speaking in Tongues (TV show)}}\nIn 2005 and 2006, Safran co-hosted a television talk show entitled ''[[Speaking in Tongues (TV show)|Speaking in Tongues]]'' with [[Father Bob Maguire]], a Catholic priest who Safran met during the filming of ''John Safran vs God''. The 12-part series broadcast on [[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS Television]] and began on 7 November 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.speakingintongues.com.au/|title=Speaking in Tongues|publisher=Special Broadcasting Service|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220150104/http://speakingintongues.com.au/|archivedate=20 February 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===''Race Relations''===\n{{Main article|John Safran's Race Relations}}\nSafran spent portions of 2007 in Los Angeles shooting a pilot entitled ''John Safran Saves America'' for American MTV in which he tried to convince [[emo]]s to fight in Iraq, hit the couch with therapists who claim they can cure people of racism, and attempted to become gay to increase his standing in Hollywood.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nma.gov.au/education/talkback_classroom/forums/2007_talkback_classroom_forums/john_safran/safran_bio/ |title=John Safran bio |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=nma.gov.au |publisher=National Museum of Australia |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> Safran stated in an interview that he hasn't heard back from the production company [[Reveille Productions]] whether the program has been purchased for production or not but as the months go on, \"the answer isn't getting any yesser\".<ref>{{cite interview |last= |first= |subject-link= |interviewer= |title=John Safran |url=http://www.amateurscientist.org/mp3/TASP-11-7-07.mp3 |date=7 November 2007 |work=Amateur Scientist |access-date= }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 ''John Safran's Race Relations'', an eight-part comedy documentary television series, was picked up by the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]].<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Summer Heights High's Chris Lilley yet to sign new deal with ABC |url=http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,,24631775-5003422,00.html |newspaper=The Courier Mail |location=Queensland, Australia |date=10 November 2008 |access-date= }}</ref> As part of this series, on 10 April 2009, John Safran took part in a [[Crucifixion#As a devotional practice|devotional crucifixion]], an [[Crucifixion in the Philippines|annual event]] occurring on [[Good Friday]] in the Philippines. Safran was crucified in Barangay Kapitangan, [[Paombong]], Bulacan, just outside Manila along with three other men and one woman.<ref>{{cite news|title=Comic nailed to cross for 'forensic' insight |url=http://news.ninemsn.com.au/entertainment/800255/comic-nailed-to-cross-for-forensic-insight |newspaper=9 News |date=11 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090413190752/http://news.ninemsn.com.au/entertainment/800255/comic-nailed-to-cross-for-forensic-insight |archivedate=13 April 2009 }}</ref> He had nails driven through his hands and feet and hung on the cross for five minutes before being taken down and given medical treatment in a nearby tent set up for treatment.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Triple J's Safran crucified in Philippines |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2009-04-12/triple-js-safran-crucified-in-philippines/1649000 |newspaper=ABC News |location=Australia |date=12 April 2009 |access-date= }}</ref> It was nominated for a 2010 [[Logie Award]] in the category of Light Entertainment.\n\n==Radio presenter and ''Sunday Night Safran''==\n{{Main article|Sunday Night Safran}}\n{{As of|2002}} Safran had been a regular host of Melbourne [[community radio]] station [[3RRR]] (Triple R) on its morning show \"Breakfasters\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rrr.org.au/whats-going-on/news/triple-r-breakfasters-2013-line-up-announcement/|title=Triple R Breakfasters 2013 line up announcement|last=|first=|date=October 10, 2013|website=Triple R|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512182936/http://www.rrr.org.au/whats-going-on/news/triple-r-breakfasters-2013-line-up-announcement/|archive-date=2013-05-12|access-date=December 24, 2019}}</ref> Additionally, he co-hosted the weekly radio show ''Sunday Night Safran'' on national youth radio station [[Triple J]] with [[Father Bob Maguire]]. After a lengthy hiatus late 2008 due to a busy filming schedule, ''Sunday Night Safran'' returned to the airwaves on 12 July 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/SundayNightSafranArchive|title=Sunday Night Safran Archive|work=Internet Archive}}</ref> The program ended at the end of 2015.<ref name=\"nickgalvin\">{{cite news |last=Galvin |first=Nick |date=30 November 2015 |title=John Safran, Father Bob quit Triple J |url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/john-safran-father-bob-quit-triple-j-20151130-glbaz7.html |newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald |location=Sydney, New South Wales, Australia |access-date= }}</ref>\n\nThe program was iconic because the co-hosts  talked to each other for much longer than instructed to (one such incident involved Fr Bob and Safran looking up the word ''[[monstrance]]'' in a dictionary following a dispute) and referring to the audience as \"Dear Listeners\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Razer |first=Helen |date=1 December 2015 |title= ''Sunday Night Safran'' was the best kind of journalism |url=http://www.crikey.com.au/2015/12/01/sunday-night-safran-was-the-best-kind-of-journalism/ |newspaper=Crikey |location=Melbourne, Victoria, Australia |access-date= }}</ref> By Safran's own admission, Maguire and he \"only seem to talk about Scrabble and White Supremacists\".<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Oliver Burkeman, Waleed Aly and Craig Reucassel |episode-link= |url=https://soundcloud.com/triplejsundaynightsafran/oliver-burkeman-waleed-aly-and |access-date= |series=Sunday Night Safran |series-link= |first= |last= |network=Australian Broadcasting Commission |station=Triple J |date=17 March 2013 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref>\n\nDuring the program's run, Safran and Maguire were able to get interviews from people such as religious scholar [[Reza Aslan]], [[Julian Assange|Julian Assange's]] mother Christine, ''[[The Exorcist (film)|The Exorcist]]'' star [[Linda Blair]],  philosopher and [[The School of Life|School of Life]] founder [[Alain de Botton]], writer, retired prison doctor and psychiatrist [[Theodore Dalrymple]], West Memphis Three [[West Memphis Three#Damien Wayne Echols|Damien Echols]], antitheist [[Christopher Hitchens]], conspiracy theorist [[David Icke]], former white supremacist skinhead [[Frank Meeink]], pro-euthanasia doctor [[Philip Nitschke]], ''[[The Act of Killing]]'' director [[Joshua Oppenheimer]], journalist and writer [[Jon Ronson]], true crime writer and [[Ted Bundy]] co-worker [[Ann Rule]],  the Lizardman [[The Lizardman|Erik Sprague]], African-American pro-Israel political activist and Zionist [[Chlo\u00e9 Valdary]], Jewish activist against child sexual abuse [[Manny Waks]], psychic [[Lisa Williams (psychic)|Lisa Williams]] and John Safran's dad, Alex.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/safran/podcast/ |title=Sunday Night Safran: Podcast |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=triplej.net.au |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Commission |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Non-fiction writing and journalism==\nAfter discovering that a subject of his series ''Race Relations'', \"Mississippi's most notorious white supremacist\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.readings.com.au/news/john-safran-on-murder-in-mississippi |title=John Safran on Murder in Mississippi |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=30 September 2013 |website=readings.com.au |publisher=Readings |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> [[Richard Barrett (lawyer)|Richard Barrett]] had been murdered, Safran returned to Mississippi to cover the trial. In 2013 [[Penguin Books]] published Safran's memoir of his experiences on this trip, ''Murder in Mississippi'' (published as ''God'll Cut You Down'' in the US). In 2014 he received a [[Ned Kelly Awards|Ned Kelly Award]] for Best True Crime for the book.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |last=Morris |first=Linda |date=7 September 2014 |title=From Gonzo to gumshoe: John Safran's Murder in Mississippi wins best true crime award |url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/books/from-gonzo-to-gumshoe-john-safrans-murder-in-mississippi-wins-best-true-crime-award-20140906-10cr7o.html |newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald |location=Sydney, New South Wales, Australia |access-date= }}</ref> Safran writes for a number of newspapers, including the ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]''<ref>{{cite news |last=Safran |first=John |date=26 March 2014 |title=A town called malice |url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/a-town-called-malice-20140317-34waw.html?eid=socialn%3Afac-13omn1676-edtrl-other%3Annn-17%2F02%2F2014-edtrs_socialshare-all-nnn-nnn-vars-o/ |newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald |location=Sydney, New South Wales, Australia |access-date= }}</ref> and [[Vice News]].<ref name=\"johnsafran\">{{cite news |last=Safran |first=John |date=1 December 2005 |title=Word Nerd |url=https://www.vice.com/read/word-v12n11 |newspaper=Vice News |location=United States |access-date= }}</ref>\n\nSafran has also written a book about extremism in Australia, titled ''[[Depends What You Mean By Extremist]]''.  It was published in May 2017.<ref name=\"depends\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nSafran's favourite board game is [[Scrabble]]. However, he prefers to play one-on-one compared with four or more players, as one-on-one is a \"game of skill\" instead of a \"game of luck\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite episode |title=Simon Taylor, Christine Assange, Chris Stedman and Khaled Khalafalla |episode-link= |url=https://soundcloud.com/triplejsundaynightsafran/comedian-simon-taylor |access-date= |series=Sunday Night Safran |series-link= |first= |last= |network=Australian Broadcasting Commission |station=Triple J |date=15 April 2012 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> He also owns all the comprehensive Scrabble dictionaries.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Furthermore, Safran has a Scrabble Rug, a Scrabble board costume, Michael Groves Special Edition Scrabble, Hebrew Scrabble, CD Rom Scrabble, Key Ring Scrabble and a Scrabble watch.<ref name=\"johnsafran\"/>\n\nJohn Safran was painted by [[Yvette Coppersmith]] and entered in the 2009 [[Archibald Prize]]. The painting was a finalist.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/prizes/archibald/2009/28759/ |title=Archibald Prize 2009: Yvette Coppersmith |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2009 |website=artgallery.nsw.gov.au |publisher=Art Gallery of New South Wales |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>\n\nSafran has stated that he believes in a force or unifying spirit, and has some \"supernatural beliefs\".<ref name=\"abc.net.au3\">{{Cite episode |title=A Spiritual Special |episode-link= |url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/qanda/txt/s3266962.htm |access-date= |series=Q and A |series-link= |first= |last= |network=Australian Broadcasting Commission |station=ABC1 |date=18 July 2011 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> He went on to explain that he doesn't think \"these things have to be absolutely true to sort of be invigorating\". Furthermore, he thinks mysticism is \"a bit like trying to see how long you can hold your breath underwater or like driving without a seatbelt and it\u2019s just like it\u2019s fun. Like so basically religion is a bit like - trying to ban religion is like trying to ban snowboarding or something. It\u2019s just like the rituals are just - can be really fun\".<ref name=\"abc.net.au3\"/> He thinks that organised religion \"gets a pretty good break in Australia\" as they don't have to pay as much tax and are allowed to preach against homosexuals.<ref name=\"abc.net.au3\"/>\n\nSafran thinks that religious education should be allowed in schools, and disagrees that it is brainwashing.<ref name=\"abc.net.au3\"/> \n:::It\u2019s like saying if you\u2019re going to listen to heavy metal albums you\u2019re going to go on shooting sprees. It\u2019s not like having a chaplain in your school like it\u2019s the only influence that\u2019s going to be on the kid. [...] You\u2019re just going to jump into strange people, so you bump into the chaplain and he\u2019s teaching you all that strange stuff and then, I don\u2019t know, you grow up and then you\u2019ve got these cool stories about the mad chaplain at your school.<ref name=\"abc.net.au3\"/>\n\nSafran's first date was with a girl called Meg who he was doing work experience with at the ''Australian Jewish News'' in Year 10. They saw ''[[Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade]]'' together.<ref name=\"smh.com.au1\"/> At university he began a relationship with a Bolivian girl, but it ended because Safran was \"obsessed with [his] creative work\" and at 19, Safran did not want the relationship to turn into something more serious.<ref name=\"smh.com.au1\"/>\n\nSafran dated playwright [[Lally Katz]].\n\nDuring his audition for ''Race around the World'' in 1997, Safran had to provide a written submission. He was asked  \"what are the most important things in your life?\" Safran answered,\n:::Dearest judging panel,\n:::I guess I have to concede that the most important thing is love (the boy-meets-girl type). And even though I am 'in between drinks at the moment,' I will resist the temptation to become one of those cold-hearted cynical people who pretends love ain't such a big deal.\n:::Yours forever, John. XXOO\n:::PS \u2014 My CD collection comes a close second.<ref name=\"abc.net.au2\"/>\n\n==Ancestry==\nSafran is [[Ashkenazi Jewish]]. Through his father, Safran is a German Jewish, and through his mother descends from Polish Jews from [[Ka\u0142uszyn]].<ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |editor1-last=Shamri |editor1-first=A |editor2-last=Soroka |editor2-first=Sh. |date=1961 |title=Sefer Kaluszyn |trans-title=The Memorial Book of Kaluszyn |url=http://www.jewishgen.org/Yizkor/kaluszyn/kaluszyn.html |language=Yiddish |location=Tel Aviv |publisher= |isbn=}}</ref><ref name=\"abc.net.au1\"/>\n\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''John Safran'''\n|2= 2. Alexander Safran\n|3= 3. Gitla Obronczka\n|4= 4. Jacob Safran\n|5= 5. [[Bodenheimer|Grete Bodenheimer]]\n|6= 6. Jankiel Obronczki\n|7= 7. Masza\n|8= 8. Abraham Alexander Safran\n|10= 10. Alexander Bodenheimer\n|12= 12. Betzalel Mordechai Obronczki\n|13= 13. Faiga\n|14= 14. Avraham\n|15= 15. Gitel\n|24= 24. Yehu Obronczki\n|26= 26. Shimshon\n}}\n\n==Work==\n\n===Filmography===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Title\n! colspan=\"5\" | Functioned as\n|-\n! [[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n! [[Film producer|Producer]]\n! [[Television 