{"title_page": "Cornell University College of Arts and Sciences", "text_new": "{{Infobox University\n|name           = College of Arts and Sciences\n|image          = Cornell University Arts Quad from McGraw Tower.jpg\n|established    = 1865\n|type           = [[Private university|Private]]\n|city           = [[Ithaca, New York|Ithaca]]\n|state          = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|country        = U.S.\n|dean           = [[Ray Jayawardhana]]\n|faculty        = 526<ref>[http://www.dpb.cornell.edu/F_Factbook.htm Cornell Factbook<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n|undergrad      = 4,251\n|postgrad       = 1,301\n|website        = {{url|as.cornell.edu}}\n}}\n\nThe '''College of Arts and Sciences''' ('''CAS''' or '''A&S''') is a division of [[Cornell University]]. It has been part of the [[university]] since its founding, although its name has changed over time. It grants bachelor's degrees, and masters and doctorates through affiliation with the [[Cornell University Graduate School]]. Its major academic buildings are located on the Arts Quad and include some of the university's oldest buildings. The college offers courses in many fields of study and is the largest college at Cornell by undergraduate enrollment.\n\n==History==\nOriginally, the university's [[Faculty (teaching staff)|faculty]] was undifferentiated, but with the founding of the [[Cornell Law School]] in 1886 and the concomitant self-segregation of the school's [[lawyer]]s, different departments and colleges formed.\n\nInitially, the division that would become the College of Arts and Sciences was known as the Academic Department, but it was formally renamed in 1903. The College endowed the first professorships in [[American history]], [[musicology]], and [[American literature]]. Currently, the college teaches 4,100 undergraduates, with 600 full-time faculty members (and an unspecified number of lecturers) teaching 2,200 courses.<ref>[http://as.cornell.edu/information/index.cfm College of Arts and Sciences at Cornell University<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091119175622/http://as.cornell.edu/information/index.cfm |date=2009-11-19 }}</ref>\n\nProfessor [[Robert Morris Ogden]], a Professor of Psychology and expert on [[Gestalt psychology]], served as the Dean from 1923 to 1945.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Dallenbach |first=Karl M. |title=Robert Morris Ogden: 1877-1959 |journal=The American Journal of Psychology |volume=72 |issue=3 |pages=472\u2013477 |jstor=1420068 | date = September 1959   }}</ref><ref>F. S. Freeman, Harry Caplan, P. M. O\u2019Leary, [https://ecommons.cornell.edu/bitstream/handle/1813/18344/Ogden_Robert_Morris_1959.pdf?sequence=2&isAllowed=y Robert Morris Ogden: July 6, 1877 \u2014 March 2, 1959], Cornell University Faculty Memorial Statement</ref>\n\n==The Arts Quadrangle== <!-- This section is linked from [[Andrew Dickson White]] -->\n[[Image:Cornell Arts Quad 1919.jpg|thumb|250px|right|The Arts Quad in 1919]]\nThe '''Arts Quad''' is the site of Cornell's original academic buildings and is home to many of the college's programs.  On the western side of the [[Quadrangle (architecture)|quad]], at the top of [[Slope Day|Libe Slope]], are [[Morrill Hall (Cornell University)|Morrill Hall]] (completed in 1866), McGraw Hall (1872) and White Hall (1868).  These simple but elegant buildings, built with native [[Cayuga Lake|Cayuga]] [[bluestone]], reflect [[Ezra Cornell]]'s [[utilitarianism]] and are known as Stone Row. Ezra Cornell's statue, dating back to 1919, stands between Morrill and McGraw Halls.  Across from this statue, in front of Goldwin Smith Hall, sits the statue of [[Andrew Dickson White]], Cornell's other co-founder and its first president.\n\nLincoln Hall (1888) also stands on the eastern face of the quad next to Goldwin Smith Hall. On the northern face are the [[dome]]d Sibley Hall and Tjaden Hall (1883).  Just off of the quad on the Slope, next to Tjaden, stands the [[Herbert F. Johnson Museum of Art]], designed by [[I. M. Pei]].  Stimson Hall (1902), [[Cornell University Library|Olin Library]] (1959) and [[Cornell University Library|Uris Library]] (1892), with Cornell's landmark clocktower, McGraw Tower, stand on the southern end of the quad.\n\nOlin Library replaced Boardman Hall (1892), the original location of the [[Cornell Law School]]. In 1992, an underground addition was made to the quad with Kroch Library, an extension of Olin Library that houses several special collections of the [[Cornell University Library]], including the Division of Rare and Manuscript Collections.<ref>[http://rmc.library.cornell.edu Division of Rare and Manuscript Collections<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n[[File:Inside Klarman Hall, Cornell University.jpg|thumb|right|The former exterior of Goldwin Smith Hall is integrated into the cafe inside Klarman Hall]]\nKlarman Hall, the first new humanities building at Cornell in over 100 years, opened in 2016.<ref name=\"Wheeler\">{{cite news|last1=Wheeler|first1=Simon|title=Klarman Hall opens at Cornell University|url=https://www.ithacajournal.com/story/news/local/2016/02/01/klarman-hall-opens-cornell-university/79512706/|accessdate=4 April 2018|publisher=The Ithaca Journal|date=1 February 2016}}</ref> Klarman houses the offices of Comparative Literature and Romance Studies.<ref name=\"Wheeler\" /> The building is connected to, and surrounded on three sides by, Goldwin Smith Hall and fronts East Avenue.<ref name=\"Wheeler\" />\n\nLegends and lore about the Arts Quad and its statues can be found at [[Cornelliana#Arts Quad statues|Cornelliana]].\n\n==Academics==\n\n===Majors===\n[[Image:Arts Quad and Goldwin Smith Hall.jpg|right|thumb|Goldwin Smith Hall]]\n[[File:Morrill Hall, Cornell University, Ithaca, New York.jpg|right|thumb|Morrill Hall with McGraw hall behind it]]\nThe College of Arts and Sciences offers both [[undergraduate]] and [[graduate school|graduate]] (through the [[Cornell University Graduate School|Graduate School]]) degrees. The only undergraduate degree is the [[Bachelor of Arts]]. However, students may enroll in the dual-degree program, which allows them to pursue programs of study in two colleges and receive two different degrees.<ref>[http://www.arts.cornell.edu/programs/dualdeg.php College of Arts and Sciences at Cornell University<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060715203045/http://www.arts.cornell.edu/programs/dualdeg.php |date=2006-07-15 }}</ref>\nThe faculties within the college are:\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Cornell Africana Studies and Research Center|Africana Studies and Research Center]]*\n* American Studies\n* Anthropology\n* Archaeology\n* Asian-American Studies\n* Asian Studies\n* Astronomy/Astrophysics\n* Biology (with the [[Cornell University College of Agriculture and Life Sciences|College of Agriculture and Life Sciences]])\n* Biology & Society Major (with the Colleges of [[Cornell University College of Agriculture and Life Sciences|Agriculture and Life Sciences]] and [[Cornell University College of Human Ecology|Human Ecology]])\n* Chemistry and Chemical Biology\n* China and Asia-pacific Studies\n* Classics\n* Cognitive Studies\n* College Scholar Program (frees up to 40 selected students in each class from all degree requirements and allows them to fashion a plan of study conducive to achieving their ultimate intellectual goals; a senior thesis is required)\n* Comparative Literature\n* Computer Science (with the [[Cornell University College of Engineering|College of Engineering]])\n* Earth and Atmospheric Sciences (with the Colleges of [[Cornell University College of Agriculture and Life Sciences|Agriculture and Life Sciences]] and [[Cornell University College of Engineering|Engineering]])\n* Economics\n* English\n* Feminist, Gender, and Sexuality Studies\n* German Studies\n* Government\n* [[Cornell University Department of History|History]]\n* History of Art\n* Human Biology\n* Independent Major\n* Information Science  (with the [[Cornell University College of Agriculture and Life Sciences|College of Agriculture and Life Sciences]] and [[Cornell University College of Engineering|College of Engineering]])\n* Jewish Studies\n* John S. Knight Institute for Writing in the Disciplines\n* Latin American Studies\n* Latino Studies\n* Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, and Transgender Studies\n* Linguistics\n* Mathematics\n* Medieval Studies\n* Modern European Studies Concentration\n* Music\n* Near Eastern Studies\n* Philosophy\n* Physics\n* Psychology\n* Religious Studies\n* Romance Studies\n* Russian\n* Science and Technology Studies\n* Society for the Humanities\n* Sociology\n* Theatre, Film, and Dance\n* Visual Studies Undergraduate Concentration\n{{colend}}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki>Africana Studies was an independent center reporting directly to the Provost until July 1, 2011.\n\n==Admissions==\nAdmission into the college is extremely competitive. The undergraduate program's 9.9% acceptance rate is below Cornell's 10.9% overall undergraduate acceptance rate. Furthermore, Arts and Sciences has the second lowest acceptance rate of any Cornell college, behind the [[Charles H. Dyson School of Applied Economics and Management|Dyson School]] (6.5%). <ref>http://irp.dpb.cornell.edu/university-factbook/undergraduate-admissions</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://as.cornell.edu//}}\n\n{{Cornell}}\n\n{{Coord|42|26|57|N|76|29|1|W|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arts and Sciences}}\n[[Category:Cornell University]]\n[[Category:Colleges and schools of Cornell University]]\n[[Category:1865 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox University\n|name           = College of Arts and Sciences\n|image          = Cornell University Arts Quad from McGraw Tower.jpg\n|established    = 1865\n|type           = [[Private university|Private]]\n|city           = [[Ithaca, New York|Ithaca]]\n|state          = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|country        = U.S.\n|dean           = [[Ray Jayawardhana]]\n|faculty        = 526<ref>[http://www.dpb.cornell.edu/F_Factbook.htm Cornell Factbook<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n|undergrad      = 4,251\n|postgrad       = 1,301\n|website        = {{url|as.cornell.edu}}\n}}\n\nThe '''College of Arts and Sciences''' ('''CAS''' or '''A&S''') is a division of [[Cornell University]]. It has been part of the [[university]] since its founding, although its name has changed over time. It grants bachelor's degrees, and masters and doctorates through affiliation with the [[Cornell University Graduate School]]. Its major academic buildings are located on the Arts Quad and include some of the university's oldest buildings. The college offers courses in many fields of study and is the largest college at Cornell by undergraduate enrollment.\n\n==History==\nOriginally, the university's [[Faculty (teaching staff)|faculty]] was undifferentiated, but with the founding of the [[Cornell Law School]] in 1886 and the concomitant self-segregation of the school's [[lawyer]]s, different departments and colleges formed.\n\nInitially, the division that would become the College of Arts and Sciences was known as the Academic Department, but it was formally renamed in 1903. The College endowed the first professorships in [[American history]], [[musicology]], and [[American literature]]. Currently, the college teaches 4,100 undergraduates, with 600 full-time faculty members (and an unspecified number of lecturers) teaching 2,200 courses.<ref>[http://as.cornell.edu/information/index.cfm College of Arts and Sciences at Cornell University<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091119175622/http://as.cornell.edu/information/index.cfm |date=2009-11-19 }}</ref>\n\nProfessor [[Robert Morris Ogden]], a Professor of Psychology and expert on [[Gestalt psychology]], served as the Dean from 1923 to 1945.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Dallenbach |first=Karl M. |title=Robert Morris Ogden: 1877-1959 |journal=The American Journal of Psychology |volume=72 |issue=3 |pages=472\u2013477 |jstor=1420068 | date = September 1959   }}</ref><ref>F. S. Freeman, Harry Caplan, P. M. O\u2019Leary, [https://ecommons.cornell.edu/bitstream/handle/1813/18344/Ogden_Robert_Morris_1959.pdf?sequence=2&isAllowed=y Robert Morris Ogden: July 6, 1877 \u2014 March 2, 1959], Cornell University Faculty Memorial Statement</ref>\n\n==The Arts Quadrangle== <!-- This section is linked from [[Andrew Dickson White]] -->\n[[Image:Cornell Arts Quad 1919.jpg|thumb|250px|right|The Arts Quad in 1919]]\nThe '''Arts Quad''' is the site of Cornell's original academic buildings and is home to many of the college's programs.  On the western side of the [[Quadrangle (architecture)|quad]], at the top of [[Slope Day|Libe Slope]], are [[Morrill Hall (Cornell University)|Morrill Hall]] (completed in 1866), McGraw Hall (1872) and White Hall (1868).  These simple but elegant buildings, built with native [[Cayuga Lake|Cayuga]] [[bluestone]], reflect [[Ezra Cornell]]'s [[utilitarianism]] and are known as Stone Row. Ezra Cornell's statue, dating back to 1919, stands between Morrill and McGraw Halls.  Across from this statue, in front of Goldwin Smith Hall, sits the statue of [[Andrew Dickson White]], Cornell's other co-founder and its first president.\n\nLincoln Hall (1888) also stands on the eastern face of the quad next to Goldwin Smith Hall. On the northern face are the [[dome]]d Sibley Hall and Tjaden Hall (1883).  Just off of the quad on the Slope, next to Tjaden, stands the [[Herbert F. Johnson Museum of Art]], designed by [[I. M. Pei]].  Stimson Hall (1902), [[Cornell University Library|Olin Library]] (1959) and [[Cornell University Library|Uris Library]] (1892), with Cornell's landmark clocktower, McGraw Tower, stand on the southern end of the quad.\n\nOlin Library replaced Boardman Hall (1892), the original location of the [[Cornell Law School]]. In 1992, an underground addition was made to the quad with Kroch Library, an extension of Olin Library that houses several special collections of the [[Cornell University Library]], including the Division of Rare and Manuscript Collections.<ref>[http://rmc.library.cornell.edu Division of Rare and Manuscript Collections<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n[[File:Inside Klarman Hall, Cornell University.jpg|thumb|right|The former exterior of Goldwin Smith Hall is integrated into the cafe inside Klarman Hall]]\nKlarman Hall, the first new humanities building at Cornell in over 100 years, opened in 2016.<ref name=\"Wheeler\">{{cite news|last1=Wheeler|first1=Simon|title=Klarman Hall opens at Cornell University|url=https://www.ithacajournal.com/story/news/local/2016/02/01/klarman-hall-opens-cornell-university/79512706/|accessdate=4 April 2018|publisher=The Ithaca Journal|date=1 February 2016}}</ref> Klarman houses the offices of Comparative Literature and Romance Studies.<ref name=\"Wheeler\" /> The building is connected to, and surrounded on three sides by, Goldwin Smith Hall and fronts East Avenue.<ref name=\"Wheeler\" />\n\nLegends and lore about the Arts Quad and its statues can be found at [[Cornelliana#Arts Quad statues|Cornelliana]].\n\n==Academics==\n\n===Majors===\n[[Image:Arts Quad and Goldwin Smith Hall.jpg|right|thumb|Goldwin Smith Hall]]\n[[File:Morrill Hall, Cornell University, Ithaca, New York.jpg|right|thumb|Morrill Hall with McGraw hall behind it]]\nThe College of Arts and Sciences offers both [[undergraduate]] and [[graduate school|graduate]] (through the [[Cornell University Graduate School|Graduate School]]) degrees. The only undergraduate degree is the [[Bachelor of Arts]]. However, students may enroll in the dual-degree program, which allows them to pursue programs of study in two colleges and receive two different degrees.<ref>[http://www.arts.cornell.edu/programs/dualdeg.php College of Arts and Sciences at Cornell University<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060715203045/http://www.arts.cornell.edu/programs/dualdeg.php |date=2006-07-15 }}</ref>\nThe faculties within the college are:\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Cornell Africana Studies and Research Center|Africana Studies and Research Center]]*\n* American Studies\n* Anthropology\n* Archaeology\n* Asian-American Studies\n* Asian Studies\n* Astronomy/Astrophysics\n* Biology (with the [[Cornell University College of Agriculture and Life Sciences|College of Agriculture and Life Sciences]])\n* Biology & Society Major (with the Colleges of [[Cornell University College of Agriculture and Life Sciences|Agriculture and Life Sciences]] and [[Cornell University College of Human Ecology|Human Ecology]])\n* Chemistry and Chemical Biology\n* China and Asia-pacific Studies\n* Classics\n* Cognitive Studies\n* College Scholar Program (frees up to 40 selected students in each class from all degree requirements and allows them to fashion a plan of study conducive to achieving their ultimate intellectual goals; a senior thesis is required)\n* Comparative Literature\n* Computer Science (with the [[Cornell University College of Engineering|College of Engineering]])\n* Earth and Atmospheric Sciences (with the Colleges of [[Cornell University College of Agriculture and Life Sciences|Agriculture and Life Sciences]] and [[Cornell University College of Engineering|Engineering]])\n* Economics\n* English\n* Feminist, Gender, and Sexuality Studies\n* German Studies\n* Government\n* [[Cornell University Department of History|History]]\n* History of Art\n* Human Biology\n* Independent Major\n* Information Science  (with the [[Cornell University College of Agriculture and Life Sciences|College of Agriculture and Life Sciences]] and [[Cornell University College of Engineering|College of Engineering]])\n* Jewish Studies\n* John S. Knight Institute for Writing in the Disciplines\n* Latin American Studies\n* Latino Studies\n* Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, and Transgender Studies\n* Linguistics\n* Mathematics\n* Medieval Studies\n* Modern European Studies Concentration\n* Music\n* Near Eastern Studies\n* Philosophy\n* Physics\n* Psychology\n* Religious Studies\n* Romance Studies\n* Russian\n* Science and Technology Studies\n* Society for the Humanities\n* Sociology\n* Theatre, Film, and Dance\n* Visual Studies Undergraduate Concentration\n{{colend}}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki>Africana Studies was an independent center reporting directly to the Provost until July 1, 2011.\n\n==Admissions==\nAdmission into the college is extremely competitive. The undergraduate program's 9.9% acceptance rate is below the 10.9% overall acceptance rate of Cornell itself. Furthermore, Arts and Sciences has the second lowest acceptance rate of any Cornell college, behind the [[Charles H. Dyson School of Applied Economics and Management|Dyson School]] (6.5%) . <ref>http://irp.dpb.cornell.edu/university-factbook/undergraduate-admissions</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://as.cornell.edu//}}\n\n{{Cornell}}\n\n{{Coord|42|26|57|N|76|29|1|W|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arts and Sciences}}\n[[Category:Cornell University]]\n[[Category:Colleges and schools of Cornell University]]\n[[Category:1865 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Xtreambar", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAdmissions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cornell_University_College_of_Arts_and_Sciences"}
