ine]]s {{convert|8450|shp|kW|abbr=on}}; \n*2 [[DT-59]] boost gas turbines {{convert|22000|shp|kW|abbr=on}} ; \n*'''Total:''' {{convert|60900|shp|kW|abbr=on}}\n*'''or'''\n*2x M90FR FRU 20 (25/28) MW boost , 2x cruise [[M70FRU-2]] 14 MW , 8 MW\n*total=56\u201368 MW\n|Ship speed={{convert|30|kn|km/h mph|abbr=on}}\n|Ship range={{convert|4,850|nmi|km mi|abbr=on}} at {{convert|14|kn|km/h mph|abbr=on}}\n|Ship endurance=30 days\n|Ship complement=200\n|Ship sensors=*'''Air search radar:''' Fregat M2M\n*'''Surface search radar:''' 3Ts-25 Garpun-B, MR-212/201-1, Nucleus-2 6000A\n*'''Fire control radar:''' JSC 5P-10 Puma FCS, 3R14N-11356 FCS, MR-90 Orekh SAM FCS\n|Ship EW=*'''EW Suite:''' TK-25-5; \n*'''Countermeasures:''' \n*4 \u00d7 KT-216\n|Ship armament=*1 \u00d7 100 mm [[A-190 Arsenal]] naval gun \n*8 (2 \u00d7 4) UKSK [[Vertical Launch System|VLS cells]] for [[3M-54 Kalibr|Kalibr]], [[P-800 Oniks|Oniks]] or [[Zircon (missile)|Zircon]] anti-ship cruise missiles<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://rg.ru/2017/04/15/reg-ufo/rossijskaia-raketa-cirkon-dostigla-vosmi-skorostej-zvuka.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-06-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223180433/https://rg.ru/2017/04/15/reg-ufo/rossijskaia-raketa-cirkon-dostigla-vosmi-skorostej-zvuka.html |archive-date=2017-12-23 |url-status=live|df= }}</ref>\n8*[[Brahmos]] for India variants<ref>https://tass.com/defense/1045796</ref>\n*24 (2 \u00d7 12) [[Buk missile system#3S90M \"Shtil-1\"|3S90M]] VLS cells for 9M317M surface-to-air-missiles\n*2 \u00d7 [[AK-630]] CIWS\n*8 \u00d7 [[SA-16|Igla-S]] or [[9K333 Verba|Verba]] \n*2 \u00d7 double 533 mm torpedo tubes \n*1 \u00d7 [[RBU-6000]] rocket launcher\n|Ship aircraft=1 \u00d7 [[Kamov Ka-27|Ka-27]] series helicopter\n|Ship aircraft facilities=Helipad and hangar for one helicopter\n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''''Admiral Grigorovich'' class''', also referred to as '''Krivak IV class''', Russian designation '''Project 11356\u0420/\u041c''', is a class of [[frigate]]s built by the [[Yantar Shipyard]] in [[Kaliningrad]] for the [[Russian Navy]] and [[Indian Navy]]. Based on the {{sclass-|Talwar|frigate|4}}, six ships were ordered for the Russian [[Black Sea Fleet]] under two contracts in 2010 and 2011 as a complement to the {{sclass-|Admiral Gorshkov|frigate|4}} frigates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vpk-news.ru/news/29657|title=\u041d\u0430 \u0444\u0440\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0442\u0435 \"\u0410\u0434\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430\u043b \u0413\u0440\u0438\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\" \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044f\u0442 \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u043b\u0430\u0433 - \u0415\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u043a \"\u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e-\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043c\u044b\u0448\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u0443\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0440\"|language=Russian|date=11 March 2016|work=vpk-news.ru|accessdate=5 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220194700/http://vpk-news.ru/news/29657|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nBy 2010-2011, it was decided the Russian Navy will procure six vessels based on the proven {{sclass-|Talwar|frigate|4}} design, mainly due to repeated delays with production of ''Admiral Gorshkov'' frigates and because of the urgent need for new frigates necessary for modernization of the Black Sea Fleet.<ref>[https://csis-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/s3fs-public/legacy_files/files/publication/160310_Schwartz_AdmiralGorshkov_Web.pdf Admiral Gorshkov Frigate Reveals Serious Shortcomings in Russia\u2019s Naval Modernization Program] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013190110/https://csis-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/s3fs-public/legacy_files/files/publication/160310_Schwartz_AdmiralGorshkov_Web.pdf |date=2016-10-13 }} - Center for Strategic and International Studies, March 2016</ref> The Yantar Shipyard won the contract for construction of the frigates and three vessels was to be completed in four years. Previously, six ships of the same design, known as ''Talwar'' class, were built for the [[Indian Navy]] between 1999 and 2011 by the [[Baltic Shipyard]], [[Saint Petersburg]] and Yantar Shipyard, Kaliningrad.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rian.ru/defense_safety/20101218/310453755.html |title=\u0412 \u041a\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0444\u0440\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0442 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0412\u041c\u0424 \u0420\u0424 &#124; \u041e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0438 \u0431\u0435\u0437\u043e\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c &#124; \u041b\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0439 \"\u0420\u0418\u0410 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438\" |language=Russian |publisher=Rian.ru |date=18 December 2010 |accessdate=5 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101222182842/http://rian.ru/defense_safety/20101218/310453755.html |archive-date=22 December 2010 |url-status=live|df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe lead ship, {{ship|Russian frigate|Admiral Grigorovich||2}}, was laid down on 18 December 2010 and was commissioned on 11 March 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tass.ru/en/defense/861624|title=St. Andrew flag hoisted on Russia's Project 11356 lead frigate|website=[[TASS]]|date=11 March 2016|accessdate=5 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927120628/http://tass.ru/en/defense/861624|archive-date=27 September 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.usni.org/2016/06/09/russian-first-new-frigate|title=Russian Black Sea Fleet Gets First New Frigate Since Cold War|first=Sam|last=LaGrone|date=9 June 2016|website=usni.org|accessdate=5 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808100127/https://news.usni.org/2016/06/09/russian-first-new-frigate|archive-date=8 August 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nInitially, Ukrainian state-owned enterprise [[Zorya-Mashproekt]] was providing gas turbines for the Russian frigates,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.usni.org/2015/06/10/russian-navy-faces-surface-modernization-delays-without-ukrainian-engines-officials-pledge-to-sue |title=Russian Navy Faces Surface Modernization Delays Without Ukrainian Engines, Officials Pledge to Sue |date=10 June 2015 |website=usni.org |last=LaGrone |first=Sam |accessdate=5 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170120055807/https://news.usni.org/2015/06/10/russian-navy-faces-surface-modernization-delays-without-ukrainian-engines-officials-pledge-to-sue |archive-date=20 January 2017 |url-status=live|df=dmy-all }}</ref> but after the [[Ukrainian crisis]], Ukraine said it would no longer supply the engines.<ref>{{cite web |work=Jane's Defence Weekly |url=http://www.janes.com/article/55284/russia-hoping-to-export-three-sanction-hit-admiral-grigorovich-class-frigates |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016123120/http://www.janes.com/article/55284/russia-hoping-to-export-three-sanction-hit-admiral-grigorovich-class-frigates |url-status=dead|archive-date=2015-10-16 |title=Russia hoping to export three sanction-hit Admiral Grigorovich-class frigates}}</ref> Instead, Russian manufacturer [[UEC Saturn|Saturn]] was asked to supply alternative M90FR gas turbines.<ref name=\"JanesRestart\">{{cite web|last1=Jones |first1=Bruce |title=USC announces restart of Project 11356 frigates |url=http://www.janes.com/article/71185 |website=IHS Jane's 360 |accessdate=8 June 2017 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170608144433/http://www.janes.com/article/71185/usc-announces-restart-of-project-11356-frigates |archivedate=8 June 2017 |date=6 June 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSince October 2016, it was claimed the three incomplete frigates, ''Admiral Butakov'', ''Admiral Istomin'' and ''Admiral Kornilov'', that construction was suspended in 2015 due to Ukraine's refusal to supply gas turbine power plants, are considered to be sold to India.<ref>{{cite website |date=11 March 2016 |url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/india-russia-sign-16-agreements-across-multiple-sectors-3053736.html |website=firstpost.com |title=India, Russia sign 16 agreements across multiple sectors |accessdate=5 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122092350/http://www.firstpost.com/india/india-russia-sign-16-agreements-across-multiple-sectors-3053736.html |archive-date=22 November 2016 |url-status=live|df=dmy-all }}</ref> The Russian Navy has opposed this export.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rusnavyintelligence.com/2016/03/revue-de-presse-navale-du-11-mars-2016.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-04-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826075606/http://www.rusnavyintelligence.com/2016/03/revue-de-presse-navale-du-11-mars-2016.html |archive-date=2017-08-26 |url-status=live|df= }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 June 2017, the [[United Shipbuilding Corporation]] (USC) announced that it would resume construction of the last three frigates in 2018 and that the ships will later join the Russian Navy. The decision to resume the work was made following the preliminary testing of latest Russian gas turbine engines, the M70FRU (14 MW), M70FRU2 (6-8 MW) and M90FR (20 MW , maximal 25-28 MW), from the [[United Engine Corporation]], built at NPO Saturn and TurboRus plants.<ref name=\"JanesRestart\"/> With an access to alternative power plants, the ships were believed to remain in Russian service.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bmpd.livejournal.com/2644867.html |title=\u0422\u0440\u0438 \u0444\u0440\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 11356 \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0443\u0442 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043d\u044b \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0412\u041c\u0424 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0441 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u043c\u0438 \u0433\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0431\u0438\u043d\u043d\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0430\u0433\u0440\u0435\u0433\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043c\u0438 |language=ru |date=3 June 2017 |work=bmpd.livejournal.com |accessdate= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605114153/http://bmpd.livejournal.com/2644867.html |archive-date=5 June 2017 |url-status=live|df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navyrecognition.com/index.php/news/defence-news/2017/june-2017-navy-naval-forces-defense-industry-technology-maritime-security-global-news/5253-russia-to-resume-the-construction-of-the-last-three-project-11356-frigates-in-2018.html |title=Russia to resume the construction of the \"last three\" Project 11356 frigates in 2018 |language= |date=3 June 2017 |work=navyrecognition.com |accessdate= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604223955/http://navyrecognition.com/index.php/news/defence-news/2017/june-2017-navy-naval-forces-defense-industry-technology-maritime-security-global-news/5253-russia-to-resume-the-construction-of-the-last-three-project-11356-frigates-in-2018.html |archive-date=4 June 2017 |url-status=live|df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHowever, on 27 October 2018, India's Ministry of Defence and Russia negotiated deal for US$950 million deal for delivery of two ''Admiral Grigorovich''-class frigates to the Indian Navy and latter added two more of same class to be built in Indian shipyard for US$500 million<ref>https://www.thedefensepost.com/2018/11/20/india-russia-4-admiral-grigorovich-project-11356-frigates/</ref>. India in 2019. paid in full two frigates to be build in Russia and two more ships will be assembled in India\u2019s [[Goa Shipyard]] Limited upon equipping India shipyard while ships hulls build in Russia Yantar shipyard are due to bemounted on a solid foundation in next few months of 2019. after payment is received and then expected delivered is at first half of 2024. or before.<ref>https://tass.com/defense/1117199</ref><ref>https://tass.com/defense/1079625</ref> \n\nAs of February 2019, the last three vessels remain without engines.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Osborn |first1=Andrew |title=Despite Putin's swagger, Russia struggles to modernize its navy |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-military-insight/despite-putins-swagger-russia-struggles-to-modernize-its-navy-idUSKCN1QA0U7 |accessdate=21 February 2019 |agency=Reuters |date=21 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190221083335/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-military-insight/despite-putins-swagger-russia-struggles-to-modernize-its-navy-idUSKCN1QA0U7 |archive-date=21 February 2019 |url-status=live|df=dmy-all }}</ref> But during 2019. obstacles with engines are solved, Russia domestic engine M70FRU-2 testing is finished and enters serial production<ref>https://www.uecrus.com/eng/products/marine_engine/m70fru/</ref><ref>https://www.uecrus.com/rus/presscenter/odk_news/2019/?ELEMENT_ID=3085</ref> and construction of ships using that engine is ramping up.<ref>http://nrnews.ru/news/transport/106255-ekspert-rasskazal-o-sozdanii-v-rossii-dvigateley-dlya-voenno-morskogo-flota.html</ref>\n\n==Operational history==\nOn 3 November 2016, as part of [[Russian military intervention in the Syrian Civil War]], ''Admiral Grigorivich'' was deployed to the [[Mediterranean Sea]] for the first time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pravdareport.com/news/world/asia/syria/03-11-2016/136065-russia_frigate-0/ |title=Russia\u2019s state-of-the-art frigate Admiral Grigorovich sets off to Syria |newspaper=Pravda |date=3 November 2016 |accessdate=5 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104154427/http://www.pravdareport.com/news/world/asia/syria/03-11-2016/136065-russia_frigate-0/ |archive-date=4 November 2016 |url-status=live|df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 15 November 2016, it has launched Kalibr cruise missile on [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|IS]] and [[Al-Nusra Front|Al-Nusra]] targets in Syria's [[Idlib]] and [[Homs]] provinces, destroying ammunition warehouses, gathering and training centers and weapon production plants.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rt.com/news/366995-anti-terrorist-operation-carrier/|title=Russian carrier takes part in massive strikes on terrorists in Syria\u2019s Idlib & Homs provinces \u2013 MoD|newspaper=RT International|language=en-EN|access-date=2016-11-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161116153020/https://www.rt.com/news/366995-anti-terrorist-operation-carrier/|archive-date=2016-11-16|url-status=live|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sputniknews.com/military/201611151047453617-frigate-syria-missiles/|title=Russian Admiral Grigorovich Frigate Targets Terrorists in Syria With Missiles|last=Sputnik|website=sputniknews.com|access-date=2016-11-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161116101226/https://sputniknews.com/military/201611151047453617-frigate-syria-missiles/|archive-date=2016-11-16|url-status=live|df=}}</ref>\n\n''Admiral Grigorivich'' was redeployed to the Mediterranean Sea in April 2017, following the [[2017 Shayrat missile strike|US missile strikes against Syria]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usni.org/2017/04/07/russia-sends-frigate-mediterranean-following-u-s-retaliation-strike-u-s-destroyers-remain-station |title=Russia Sends Frigate to Mediterranean Following U.S. Retaliation Strike; U.S. Destroyers Remain on Station |last=LeGrone |first=Sam |website=usni.org |date=7 April 2017 |accessdate=9 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407210129/https://news.usni.org/2017/04/07/russia-sends-frigate-mediterranean-following-u-s-retaliation-strike-u-s-destroyers-remain-station |archive-date=7 April 2017 |url-status=live|df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Export==\nOn 20 November 2018, [[Rosoboronexport]] and [[Goa Shipyard]] signed US$950 million and US$500 million deal<ref>https://tass.com/defense/1117199</ref><ref>https://tass.com/defense/1079625</ref> for construction of four ''Admiral Grigorovich''-class frigates for the [[Indian Navy]]. The two frigates are to be assembled at Russia Yantar shipyard and other two at the Goa Shipyard in India<ref>https://www.thedefensepost.com/2018/11/20/india-russia-4-admiral-grigorovich-project-11356-frigates/</ref>. The construction is expected to start in 2020, with first vessel to be delivered in 2026 and second in 2027.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/india-russia-to-hammer-out-mega-navy-deal-in-goa-today/story-sgP4UUXPwkY6XtDkQadNTI.html|title=India, Russia sign $500 million navy deal for 2 stealth frigates|website=hindustantimes.com|date=20 November 2018|accessdate=6 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510142134/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/india-russia-to-hammer-out-mega-navy-deal-in-goa-today/story-sgP4UUXPwkY6XtDkQadNTI.html|archive-date=10 May 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tass.com/defense/1031650|title=Russia, India sign contracts on building 4 Project 11356 frigates|website=[[TASS]]|date=20 November 2018|accessdate=6 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427182340/http://tass.com/defense/1031650|archive-date=2019-04-27|url-status=live|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.janes.com/article/84754/india-signs-usd500-million-deal-to-licence-build-two-russian-stealth-frigates|title=India signs USD500-million deal to licence-build two Russian stealth frigates|date=21 November 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20190506193248/https://www.janes.com/article/84754/india-signs-usd500-million-deal-to-licence-build-two-russian-stealth-frigates|archivedate=6 May 2019|df=dmy-all|access-date=22 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.navyrecognition.com/index.php/news/defence-news/2019/january/6791-indian-mod-awarded-goa-shipyard-ltd-contract-for-2-talwar-frigates.html|title=Indian MoD awarded Goa Shipyard Ltd contract for 2 Talwar frigates|website=navyrecognition.com|date=31 January 2019|accessdate=6 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204014712/https://www.navyrecognition.com/index.php/news/defence-news/2019/january/6791-indian-mod-awarded-goa-shipyard-ltd-contract-for-2-talwar-frigates.html|archive-date=4 February 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Ships==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Namesake\n! Builder\n! Laid down\n! Launched\n! Commissioned\n! Fleet or Navy\n! Status\n|-\n| {{Ship|Russian frigate|Admiral Grigorovich||2}}\n| [[Ivan Grigorovich|Ivan Konstantinovich Grigorovich]]\n| [[Yantar Shipyard|Yantar]], Kaliningrad\n| 18 December 2010\n| 14 March 2014<ref>{{cite web |website=Sputnik |url=http://en.ria.ru/military_news/20140314/188432750/Russia-Floats-Out-New-Frigate-for-Black-Sea-Fleet.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140314232917/http://en.ria.ru/military_news/20140314/188432750/Russia-Floats-Out-New-Frigate-for-Black-Sea-Fleet.html |url-status=dead|archive-date=2014-03-14 |title=The Yantar shipyard in Russia\u2019s Baltic exclave of Kaliningrad on Friday floated out the first in a series of six Project 11356 frigates being built for the Black Sea Fleet, the company said}}</ref>\n| 11 March 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.i-mash.ru/news/nov_predpr/77299-psz-jantar-sdal-admirala-grigorovicha.html|title=\u041f\u0421\u0417 \"\u042f\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0440\u044c\" \u0441\u0434\u0430\u043b \"\u0410\u0434\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0413\u0440\u0438\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\u0430\" \u00bb \u0420\u0435\u0441\u0443\u0440\u0441 \u043c\u0430\u0448\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f. \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u043c\u0430\u0448\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f, \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c\u0438. \u041a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433 \u043c\u0430\u0448\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0437\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043f\u0440\u0438\u044f\u0442\u0438\u0439.|language=Russian|date=10 March 2016|website=i-mash.ru|accessdate=5 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011130239/http://www.i-mash.ru/news/nov_predpr/77299-psz-jantar-sdal-admirala-grigorovicha.html|archive-date=11 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| [[Black Sea Fleet|Black Sea]]\n| Active\n|-\n| {{ship|Russian frigate|Admiral Essen||2}}\n| [[Nikolai Essen|Nikolai Ottovich Essen]]\n| Yantar, Kaliningrad\n| 8 July 2011<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kaliningrad.ru/news/item/12885-na-zavode-yantar-zalozhili-novyj-storozhevoj-korabl-admiral-essen |title=\u041d\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0435 \"\u042f\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0440\u044c\" \u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0441\u044c \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043b\u044f \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0412\u041c\u0424 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 (\u0444\u043e\u0442\u043e) |publisher=Kaliningrad.ru |language=Russian |date=8 July 2011 |accessdate=5 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120128201256/http://kaliningrad.ru/news/item/12885-na-zavode-yantar-zalozhili-novyj-storozhevoj-korabl-admiral-essen |archive-date=28 January 2012 |url-status=dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newkaliningrad.ru/news/foto/1309138-admiral-essen.html |title=\"\u0410\u0434\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430\u043b \u043d\u043e\u043c\u0435\u0440 \u0434\u0432\u0430\": \u0444\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0435\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u0436 \"\u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u041a\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430.Ru\" |language=Russian |publisher=Newkaliningrad.ru |date=8 July 2011 |accessdate=5 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808125813/https://www.newkaliningrad.ru/news/foto/1309138-admiral-essen.html |archive-date=8 August 2016 |ur