{"title_page": "Jay Walljasper", "text_new": "'''Jay Walljasper''' is an American writer, speaker and community consusltant. He explores how new ideas in [[urban planning]], tourism, [[community development]], [[sustainability]], politics and culture can improve our lives as well as the world.\n\n==Career==\nWalljasper graduated from the [[University of Iowa]] in Iowa City, where he wrote for the ''[[Daily Iowan]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gentry|first=Samantha|title=Writer Walljasper visits Iowa City this week|url=http://www.dailyiowan.com/2011/11/07/Metro/25855.html|newspaper=The Daily Iowan|date=November 7, 2011}}</ref> He is a Sabo Fellow at Augsburg University in Minneapolis, and Communications Director for The Placemaking Fund. He has worked with organizations such as the National Geographic Society, Kresge Foundation, AARP, Kaiser Permanente, Blue Zones, Minneapolis Foundation, McKnight Foundation, Project for Public Spaces and many others.\n\nFor more than 15 years, he was editor of ''[[Utne Reader]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite news|last=Spayde|first=Jon|title=The Commons: Minneapolis author Jay Walljasper on seeking the common good beyond left and right|url=http://www.thelinemedia.com/features/walljaspercommons011211.aspx|newspaper=The Line|date=January 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Mitchard|first=Jacquelyn|title=Utne on the Rise|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7xIfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PiwEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3273,576052&dq=jay-walljasper&hl=en|newspaper=The Milwaukee Journal|date=September 1, 1991}}</ref> \n \nHis articles have also appeared in Washington Monthly, City Lab, Yes! magazine, Notre Dame magazine, ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', ''[[Midwest Living]]'', ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'', ''[[Preservation (magazine)|Preservation]]'', ''[[New Statesman]]'' (London), ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' magazine, ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' magazine, ''[[Toronto Star]]'', ''[[Tikkun (magazine)|Tikkun]]'', ''[[L.A. Weekly]]'', ''[[Yes! (U.S. magazine)|Yes!]]'', ''E'' magazine, ''[[Le Courrier]]'' (Paris), ''[[The Idler (1993)|The Idler]]'', ''Rock N Rap Confidential'', ''Planeta Humano'' (Madrid), and ''[[New Woman]]'' (Australia).  He has been a contributing editor at National Geographic Traveler and  a travel editor at ''[[Better Homes and Gardens (magazine)|Better Homes and Gardens]]''.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Bimonthly is Distant Early Warning of the Far-Out\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/03/27/us/bimonthly-is-distant-early-warning-of-the-far-out.html?scp=1&sq=jay%20walljasper&st=cse\n|publisher=The New York Times\n|date=March 27, 1988\n| first=Lindsey\n| last=Gruson\n| accessdate=May 6, 2010\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lander|first=Rachael|title=Public spaces author to lecture on libraries\u2019 importance|url=http://www.dailyiowan.com/2009/06/12/Arts/11651.html|newspaper=The Daily Iowan|date=June 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Walljasper was commissioned by the [[McKnight Foundation]] to compose an essay for their Food for Thought series addressing future challenges and opportunities in the [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul]] region.<ref>{{cite web|last=Walljasper|first=Jay|title=Mary Tyler Moore Doesn\u2019t Live Here Anymore|url=http://www.mcknight.org/system/asset/document/395/FFT_07_2013FINAL.pdf|publisher=The McKnight Foundation|date=July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Food for Thought: Mary Tyler Moore Doesn't Live Here Anymore|url=http://www.mcknight.org/newsroom/our-voice/jay-walljasper-on-mpls-st-pauls-identity-crisis|publisher=McKnight Foundation|date=July 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*''Visionaries, People and Ideas to Change Your Life,'' with Jon Spayde and Utne Reader staff (New Society, 2001) {{ISBN|978-0-86571-445-8}}\n* ''The Great Neighborhood Book'', (New Society, 2007) {{ISBN|978-0-86571-581-3}}\n*''All That We Share: How to Save the Economy, the Environment, the Internet, Democracy, Our Communities and Everything Else that Belongs to All of Us'' with [[Bill McKibben]] Introduction (2011) {{ISBN|978-1-59558-499-1}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://jaywalljasper.com/ JayWalljasper.com]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walljasper, Jay}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Iowa alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Minneapolis]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Jay Walljasper''' is an American writer, speaker and community consusltant. He explores how new ideas in [[urban planning]], tourism, [[community development]], [[sustainability]], politics and culture can improve our lives as well as the world.\n\n==Career==\nWalljasper graduated from the [[University of Iowa]] in Iowa City, where he wrote for the ''[[Daily Iowan]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gentry|first=Samantha|title=Writer Walljasper visits Iowa City this week|url=http://www.dailyiowan.com/2011/11/07/Metro/25855.html|newspaper=The Daily Iowan|date=November 7, 2011}}</ref> He is a Sabo Fellow at Augsburg University in Minneapolis, and Communications Director for The Placemaking Fund. He has worked with organizations such as the National Geographic Society, Kresge Foundation, AARP, Kaiser Permanente, Blue Zones, Minneapolis Foundation, McKnight Foundation, Project for Public Spaces and many others.  \n\nFor more than 15 years, he was editor of ''[[Utne Reader]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite news|last=Spayde|first=Jon|title=The Commons: Minneapolis author Jay Walljasper on seeking the common good beyond left and right|url=http://www.thelinemedia.com/features/walljaspercommons011211.aspx|newspaper=The Line|date=January 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Mitchard|first=Jacquelyn|title=Utne on the Rise|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7xIfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PiwEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3273,576052&dq=jay-walljasper&hl=en|newspaper=The Milwaukee Journal|date=September 1, 1991}}</ref> \n \nHis articles have also appeared in Washington Monthly, City Lab, Yes! magazine, Notre Dame magazine, ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', ''[[Midwest Living]]'', ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'', ''[[Preservation (magazine)|Preservation]]'', ''[[New Statesman]]'' (London), ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' magazine, ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' magazine, ''[[Toronto Star]]'', ''[[Tikkun (magazine)|Tikkun]]'', ''[[L.A. Weekly]]'', ''[[Yes! (U.S. magazine)|Yes!]]'', ''E'' magazine, ''[[Le Courrier]]'' (Paris), ''[[The Idler (1993)|The Idler]]'', ''Rock N Rap Confidential'', ''Planeta Humano'' (Madrid), and ''[[New Woman]]'' (Australia).  He has been a contributing editor at National Geographic Traveler and  a travel editor at ''[[Better Homes and Gardens (magazine)|Better Homes and Gardens]]''.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Bimonthly is Distant Early Warning of the Far-Out\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/03/27/us/bimonthly-is-distant-early-warning-of-the-far-out.html?scp=1&sq=jay%20walljasper&st=cse\n|publisher=The New York Times\n|date=March 27, 1988\n| first=Lindsey\n| last=Gruson\n| accessdate=May 6, 2010\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lander|first=Rachael|title=Public spaces author to lecture on libraries\u2019 importance|url=http://www.dailyiowan.com/2009/06/12/Arts/11651.html|newspaper=The Daily Iowan|date=June 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Walljasper was commissioned by the [[McKnight Foundation]] to compose an essay for their Food for Thought series addressing future challenges and opportunities in the [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul]] region.<ref>{{cite web|last=Walljasper|first=Jay|title=Mary Tyler Moore Doesn\u2019t Live Here Anymore|url=http://www.mcknight.org/system/asset/document/395/FFT_07_2013FINAL.pdf|publisher=The McKnight Foundation|date=July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Food for Thought: Mary Tyler Moore Doesn't Live Here Anymore|url=http://www.mcknight.org/newsroom/our-voice/jay-walljasper-on-mpls-st-pauls-identity-crisis|publisher=McKnight Foundation|date=July 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*''Visionaries, People and Ideas to Change Your Life,'' with Jon Spayde and Utne Reader staff (New Society, 2001) {{ISBN|978-0-86571-445-8}}\n* ''The Great Neighborhood Book'', (New Society, 2007) {{ISBN|978-0-86571-581-3}}\n*''All That We Share: How to Save the Economy, the Environment, the Internet, Democracy, Our Communities and Everything Else that Belongs to All of Us'' with [[Bill McKibben]] Introduction (2011) {{ISBN|978-1-59558-499-1}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://jaywalljasper.com/ JayWalljasper.com]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walljasper, Jay}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Iowa alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Minneapolis]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jay_Walljasper"}
{"title_page": "ATP Sofia Open", "text_new": "{{about|the new 2016 Sofia tournament|the defunct 1980\u201381 tournament|Sofia Open (tennis)}}\n{{Infobox tennis tournament\n| name                  = Sofia Open\n| type                  = [[ATP World Tour 250 series]]\n| current               = \n| founded               = 2016\n| city                  = [[Sofia]]\n| country               = Bulgaria\n| venue                 = [[Arena Armeec]]\n| category              = [[ATP World Tour 250 series]]\n| event name            = Sofia Open\n| tour                  = [[Association of Tennis Professionals#ATP World Tour|ATP World Tour]]\n| draw                  = 28{{abbr|S|Singles}} / 16{{abbr|Q|Qualification}} / 16{{abbr|D|Doubles}}\n| surface               = [[Hardcourt|Hard]] - indoors \n| prize money           = {{\u20ac|524,340|link=yes}} (2019)\n| website               = [https://sofiaopen.bg/?lang=en sofiaopen.bg]\n| completed event       = [[2019 Sofia Open|2019]]\n| men's singles         = {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Daniil Medvedev]]\n| men's doubles         = {{flagicon|NED}} [[Robin Haase]]<br />{{flagicon|NED}} [[Matw\u00e9 Middelkoop]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Sofia Open''' ({{lang-bg|\u041e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e \u043f\u044a\u0440\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u0421\u043e\u0444\u0438\u044f}}) is a men's [[ATP World Tour 250 series]] tournament played on [[Tennis court#Hard courts|indoor hard courts]]. It was held for the first time as part of the [[2016 ATP World Tour]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.novinite.com/articles/171178/Bulgaria+to+Host+ATP+250+Tournament+in+Sofia+in+February+2016 | title=Sofia hosts new 250 level event | accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref> The tournament takes place at the [[Arena Armeec]] in [[Sofia]], [[Bulgaria]].\n\n==Finals==\n\n===Singles===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!style=\"width:40px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:200px\"|Champions\n!style=\"width:200px\"|Runners-up\n!style=\"width:150px\" class=\"unsorta